  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving the living conditions of IDPs in informal settlements in Kabul through WASH</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is going to create a group of self-employed women who will pave the ways of affordable and locally appropriate sanitary napkins. Pushing the social and traditional boundaries these women will create a system of producing affordable sanitary pad in hope of starting a hygiene movement.
Sanitary napkin is universally needed product. Yet has very low presence in rural Afghanistan, partly due to its high price/ inaccessibility and partly due to the tradition of using cheaper alternatives. They therefore become the host of many infectious diseases. This is due to lack of awareness and economic inability for adopting better precautions like use of good sanitary napkins during menstruation period.  This initiative will &#x2013; 1) create hygiene awareness through REFLECT, 2) provide livelihood opportunities for women, 3) organise women groups towards formation of co-operative societies, 4) involve Govt. authorities, religious leaders, village elders and Shura members in this initiative.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will be jointly implemented by CAID and partner STARS. The overall goal of the project is better sensitization to monthly hygiene management and use of sanitary towels for women and adolescent girls who are living in informal settlements and to produce napkins at marketable level and create livelihood opportunities for these women. Below activities will be taken to serve this purpose: 
- Conduct WASH sensitization sessions including menstrual hygiene with MEN community leaders /members
-  Conduct awareness raising sessions on menstrual hygiene management with 400 women and adolescent girls
- Provision of dignity kits to 400 women and adolescent  girls
- Selection of 400 women and formation of 30 women groups
- Literacy  and hygiene training (REFLECT methodology) to 30 women groups
- Training on sanitary pad making  for 400 women and distribution of sewing machine and raw materials 
- Meeting with women&apos;s group</narrative>
  </description>
